  <!-- ST HELENS HOUSING STOCK - UNIQUE SECTION -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f1f5f9;">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="pf-section-label">LOCAL EXPERTISE</span>
      <h2>St Helens Housing Stock. What Our Engineers Find Most.</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">St Helens has a distinctive mix of housing built across five different eras, each with its own plumbing characteristics. Our engineers have attended hundreds of St Helens properties and know what to expect before they arrive.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;align-items:flex-start;">
            <div style="background:var(--orange);color:#fff;border-radius:6px;padding:0.3rem 0.7rem;font-family:'Barlow Condensed',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:0.85rem;white-space:nowrap;flex-shrink:0;">WA10</div>
            <div>
              <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Town Centre Victorian and Edwardian Terraces</strong>
              <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">The dense terraced streets of WA10 were built primarily for glass workers and the broader industrial workforce during the late Victorian and Edwardian periods. These properties share characteristics with their Liverpool counterparts: gravity-fed hot water systems supplied from cold water tanks in the loft, original or once-replaced copper pipework, and drain layouts that were designed for a different era. Many WA10 terraces have been converted to HMOs over the decades, and these multi-occupancy layouts can create complex plumbing faults where problems in one flat affect water supply to several others. We handle HMO call-outs across WA10 regularly and understand the additional complexity they involve.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;align-items:flex-start;">
            <div style="background:var(--orange);color:#fff;border-radius:6px;padding:0.3rem 0.7rem;font-family:'Barlow Condensed',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:0.85rem;white-space:nowrap;flex-shrink:0;">WA11</div>
            <div>
              <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Haydock and Rainford</strong>
              <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Haydock is predominantly post-war semi-detached and detached housing stock, much of it built between the 1950s and 1970s. Properties of this era were built with copper pipework that is now reaching the end of its design life in many homes. Boilers in these properties are frequently the original 1970s and 1980s back boilers or early combination units that have exceeded their working life. Rainford by contrast has a mix of older village housing and newer private estates. We attend Haydock and Rainford regularly and carry stock for the most common faults found in this generation of housing.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;align-items:flex-start;">
            <div style="background:var(--orange);color:#fff;border-radius:6px;padding:0.3rem 0.7rem;font-family:'Barlow Condensed',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:0.85rem;white-space:nowrap;flex-shrink:0;">WA12</div>
            <div>
              <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Newton-le-Willows and Earlestown</strong>
              <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Newton-le-Willows is a market town with a notably varied property mix. The streets around Earlestown station contain Victorian and Edwardian terraced housing with older plumbing layouts, while the outskirts of Newton include large private estates built from the 1980s onwards with modern combi boiler systems. The M6 corridor around Newton has also seen significant commercial and logistics development, and we provide 24/7 commercial plumbing cover across WA12 at the same fixed rates as our residential service. Newton-le-Willows also has a higher proportion of buy-to-let properties than much of St Helens borough, and we work with landlords and letting agents across WA12 to stay on top of gas safety compliance.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;align-items:flex-start;">
            <div style="background:var(--orange);color:#fff;border-radius:6px;padding:0.3rem 0.7rem;font-family:'Barlow Condensed',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:0.85rem;white-space:nowrap;flex-shrink:0;">WA9 WN5</div>
            <div>
              <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Thatto Heath, Billinge and Surrounding Villages</strong>
              <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">The villages surrounding St Helens town, including Billinge, Seneley Green and Thatto Heath, contain a mix of older cottage-style properties and 1960s to 1980s local authority housing. The former mining communities in this area have older heating systems that predate the widespread adoption of combination boilers. Many properties here still have vented hot water cylinders and older heating configurations that require an engineer who understands how these systems work. Billinge in particular sits on the boundary with Wigan borough and the housing stock here reflects that transition between the two areas.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
